##Diagnosis → cure → plasma donation → return to work | 39 days of a Wuhan nurse's anti-epidemic

The papernews

The function introduction, has the connotation the current politics new media

From the paper, xeroxa

"I called my supervisor to tell him I was going back to work and he wouldn't put me in isolation because I had just recovered. I asked for permission, and then the leaders agreed,"The Paper, a respiratory nurse at Puren Hospital in Wuhan, told The Paper news on February 26.

After the outbreak, Han Xiru was sent to the hospital on January 19, Jinyintan hospital support, then infected with new crown pneumonia, treatment 8 days after recovery from hospital. After nearly half a month in isolation, she donated 300 milliliters of plasma. Donate plasma that day, she called the leadership request to return to work, the next day to Pulen hospital opened up the isolation ward, and colleagues fight side by side.

Support first-line, confirmed, cure, isolation, plasma donation, return to work, so far, Han Shiru anti-epidemic has 39 days.

In fact, when she was diagnosed, Han Xiru was also very worried, but she knew not to show it, because fifty-year-old parents will be more worried about more anxiety. After hospitalization, she actively cooperated with the treatment and soon recovered and was discharged.

Going through a double life as a paramedic and a patient, Han said that as a patient friend, she wanted to tell other patients not to be too burdened psychologically and to actively cooperate with the treatment. As a paramedic, she wants patients to trust that they will do everything they can to help, and that their needs will be met. During the anti-epidemic period, Han Xiru hope that medical staff and patients should understand each other and understand each other to win the war together.

Han Shiru dictated

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Han Xiru is caring for patients at Golden Pond Hospital. All images in this article are provided by the interviewees

Support: Come to the isolation ward of Golden Pond Hospital

My name is Han Shiru. I've been working as a nurse in respiratory medicine at Purim Hospital for eight years.

Since the outbreak, I've been on the front lines, and I never thought I'd be infected.

In the first half of January, more and more patients came to Puren hospital with fever. Many of these patients have recurrent fever, or even high fever symptoms, the patient's CT film is not the same as the flu patient. We put these patients in isolation rooms.

On the afternoon of January 18, I received a phone call from my supervisor, saying that the hospital wanted to assign more senior nurses to support the newly diagnosed patients of the Golden Pool Hospital. I was one of the three nurses tentatively selected by the hospital, ask Me and my parents if they agree to go.

I was a little worried about not being afraid, but the hospital trusted me enough to let me go, so I decided to support the Golden Pool Hospital. I called my parents for advice, and I could hear that they were worried, but they understood and supported me.

On the morning of January 19, I and two other colleagues reported to the hospital.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Han Shiru and her colleagues are in the hospital room

Diagnosis: I got the infection without any symptoms?

Came to the Golden Pool Hospital, we carried out various matters of training.

The first two days I worked here, I just couldn't get used to it. We spent four hours in a hospital room in Hazmat suits. Four hours of no food, no drink, no toilet, I can bear it, but the protective clothing is too thick, very hot, choking, I in the ward dizzy headache, really uncomfortable. Meanwhile, I was sweating like a pig, and every time I came out of the ward, I was drenched in sweat.

Golden Pool Hospital colleagues often deal with infectious patients, has been very used to, nursing patients are skilled. They gave me a lot of help, in the process, I also learned a lot of infectious disease care knowledge. After a few days, I got used to the protective gear.

At that time, Jinyintan hospital treated all the confirmed patients transferred from various hospitals, my ward has about 50 patients, I and two colleagues are responsible for more than 20 patients.

The patient has no family member to accompany, we not only need to carry on the blood collection, the infusion and so on medical care, also needs to take care of the patient to eat, to drink, to go to the toilet and so on life care, the work is really quite heavy.

We were understaffed, and sometimes we had to work the night shift after an eight hour day shift, from 1 a.m. to 8 a.m. , working round the clock.

After working for a few days, the hospital routinely arranged nucleic acid tests for medical staff. The next day, I was given a day off at home, according to the schedule. On the first day of the Lunar New Year (January 25) , my parents drove me to work in the hospital. On the way to work, I learned that I had new coronary pneumonia.

At that time, I received a phone call from my colleagues at the Golden Pond Hospital that I tested positive for nucleic acid, let me return to the hospital as soon as possible for treatment.

My first reaction to the news was: How is that possible? How did I get infected when I didn't have any symptoms? I doubt it, but the answer on the other end of the phone is a resounding yes.

I was terrified, but I kept trying to convince myself that it was okay. My parents were around, and they were both in their 50s. I couldn't show worry, or they'd be even more worried. My parents also considered my emotions, and in turn comforted me by saying, "it doesn't matter, active treatment will be fine. "

When I got back to the hospital, I had another nucleic acid test, and it was positive, and I was in the hospital.

Later, the parents also separately checked the CT, fortunately, their lungs are not abnormal, I did not infect them.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Han xiru donated plasma

Cure: active treatment, 8 days discharge

I worked directly with confirmed patients, both in the respiratory department at Pulen Hospital and in the Golden Pool. So, I really don't know when I got it.

In the first few days after my hospitalization, my body gradually developed symptoms and I began to lose my appetite. I wanted to eat, but I still ate very little every day.

Although I was very afraid, but to see the other patients in the ward with high fever, cough, I think my condition should be mild, secretly happy, fortunately found in time, early treatment.

Slowly, my mind got a little better. My parents sometimes call me to ask me if I'm not feeling well. I don't usually pass on negative news to them. I don't want them to worry about me.

The doctor prescribed me some anti-viral and anti-infective drugs. They take good care of me. The hospital director and other leaders learned of my situation, but also specially came to visit me. I'm touched.

Originally, my condition was not serious, plus active treatment, about a week later, I did the nucleic acid test has turned negative, I was discharged on February 3.

I'm supposed to go home and be quarantined for half a month. In the meantime, I stayed in my room, ate alone, and spent my time in isolation.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Han Xiru and blood center staff photo

Return to work: After fighting, the leadership agreed to return to the first line of work

Just during the quarantine, I watched on TV the head of the Golden Pool Hospital appealing for blood donations from recovered new-pneumonia patients. I got the idea to donate plasma.

On February 16th, I donated 300 milliliters of plasma.

I then called the head of the Nursing Department at Pulen hospital to explain my desire to return to the front line. After listening to the leadership is very hesitant, considering I just recovered, the leadership said back to work can, but not to the first line, can only go to the general ward, take care of other patients.

I insisted on going back to the isolation ward to take care of the new pneumonia. On the one hand, I have been in the Golden Pool Hospital support, has learned a lot of knowledge and experience in this area. On the other hand, as far as I can tell, recovered patients don't seem to be re-infected. Based on these two points, I think I go to the front line work, the risk is not big, as long as the good protection, should not be infected.

After I fought, the boss finally let me go to the front line. At that time, Pulen hospital had just opened a 10th Ward, for the treatment of confirmed patients, so I naturally began to work in the 10th Ward.

On February 17th, I went to work. With the foundation of working in the Golden Pool Hospital, I started working in Puren hospital more quickly.

When it comes to our patients, we tend to encourage them. There is an aunt in the ward, a family of three all infected with new crown pneumonia, the condition is more serious, her husband has died because of this. She lives in a hospital room with her son and is in a negative mood every day. Once, my aunt asked me secretly, "can this disease be cured after all? Will we die? " I said, "It will be cured, don't put so much pressure on yourself, look at you now, you can get out of bed, go to the toilet, and eat some good food. It's already getting better, have faith in yourself. " Later, the aunt's state of mind gradually improved, and I'm getting better. Now, she and her son are just days away from being released from the hospital.

I went from being a paramedic to being a patient, and from being a patient to being a paramedic. As a patient friend, I would like to tell those who are receiving treatment, must maintain a good attitude, actively cooperate with the treatment, now the cure rate is higher and higher, do not worry too much. As a paramedic, I want patients to trust that we will do everything we can to treat them and to meet their needs.

At present, the epidemic prevention and control work is still severe, the daily work pressure and mental stress of medical staff are very big, we see patients died in vain, but also very sad and helpless. In Special Times, I hope that medical staff and patients will understand and understand each other and win the war together.

This issue is edited by Xing Tan
